SIMPLE: repulsion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repulsion
<hw>Re*pul"sion</hw> <pr>(r?-p?l"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>repulsio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧pulsion</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of repulsing or repelling, or the state of
being repulsed or repelled.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A feeling of violent offence or disgust;
repugnance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The power, either inherent or
due to some physical action, by which bodies, or the particles of
bodies, are made to recede from each other, or to resist each other's
nearer approach; <as>as, molecular <ex>repulsion</ex>; electrical
<ex>repulsion</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repulsive</ent>⟦br⟧
